{"title":"Influence of Camera-LiDAR Configuration on 3D Object Detection for Autonomous Driving","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Evaluating how different camera and LiDAR placements/parameters affect 3D object detection is costly and slow, and existing works lack a unified criterion that applies to both sensors in fusion settings.","method":"Introduce a unified, information-theoretic surrogate metric that predicts perception performance from ground-truth 3D bounding boxes without re-collecting data or retraining models. First, construct a Probabilistic Occupancy Grid (POG) over ROI voxels from dataset bounding boxes. Model both sensors via ray casting (LiDAR as rotating, vertically distributed rays; camera as rays from resized image pixels) and use Bresenham’s line algorithm to identify voxels traversed by each sensor’s rays. Compute conditional POG and entropies to obtain per-sensor information gain (S-MIG) and combine camera/LiDAR via a λ-weighted unified metric (S-MS). This metric correlates with mAP across fusion detectors and object classes, enabling rapid configuration evaluation."},{"problem":"There is no practical, systematic pipeline to quantify the impact of realistic camera–LiDAR configuration choices on multi-sensor 3D detection performance across modern fusion algorithms.","method":"Build an automated CARLA-based framework to generate nuScenes-style datasets under multiple realistic LiDAR placements (Center, Pyramid, Line, Trapezoid) and camera FOV setups (Wide vs. Narrow), then train/evaluate representative fusion methods (Transfusion, BEVFusion, PointAugmenting) with nuScenes mAP. Experiments show configuration alone can change mAP by up to 30%; Wide cameras generally outperform Narrow by up to 10%, and Trapezoid LiDAR often yields the best results. Detection performance increases with the proposed S-MS metric, validating its predictive power for configuration assessment."}]}
